<div id="review_256147737" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/256147737" />
    <a title="Ana" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7278411-ana"><img alt="Ana" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1528404309p2/7278411.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/256147737?book_show_action=true">Jan 04, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ana" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ana" href="/user/show/7278411-ana">Ana</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7278411-ana?shelf=lovey-dovey">lovey-dovey</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7278411-ana?shelf=historical-romance">historical-romance</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer256147737" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer896405233930102745">I really don&apos;t understand why I went through with this to the end. It was predictable and boring (most of the time at least) and so freaking cliche that at one point I had a feeling I should just throw the book out the window and be done with it.<br/><br/>Of course, I made the mistake of selecting this book to keep me company on my five hour train ride, and since no one else in the whole bloody compartment had the goodwill to let me borrow one of their books to keep me sane, I simply had to cope with fini</span>
  <span id="freeText896405233930102745" style="display:none">I really don't understand why I went through with this to the end. It was predictable and boring (most of the time at least) and so freaking cliche that at one point I had a feeling I should just throw the book out the window and be done with it.<br /><br />Of course, I made the mistake of selecting this book to keep me company on my five hour train ride, and since no one else in the whole bloody compartment had the goodwill to let me borrow one of their books to keep me sane, I simply had to cope with finishing this.<br /><br />I may sound a bit biased and angry about this, but let me tell you exactly why this is something you probably shouldn't read (unless you're into those sort of predictable, shallow, cliche books, in which case go right ahead!). First of all, the depth of the characters is completely nonexistent. I don't think I've ever read a book that put so much emphasis on physical appearance as "A Rose In Winter". I mean, the heroine, Erienne, was your typical goddess looking lady, who was apparently the only beautiful woman around, because otherwise I can't explain why any man who ever saw her wanted to cop a feel or rape her! I mean seriously? It seems to me like Mrs. Woodiwiss was a bit of a sexist towards men because for god's sake, no matter how beautiful she is, unless she's part Veela I can assure you not every man is going to sexually harass her the moment he sees her! <br /><br />Anyway, the heroine was way too one-dimensional for my liking. Not to mention the fact that she was shallow to the max! Most of her reasons for rejecting husband material were based on looks alone, and of course she couldn't be happy with the hideous man who lavished her with gifts and love, she had to go for the extremely (and apparently only) handsome guy! Can you get more shallow than that?<br /><br />Secondly, the damsel in distress angle is so overdone! And in this case, regardless of the fact that it was already cliche to begin with, she used it at least a dozen times throughout the book! It seemed like every twenty or so pages, Erienne was being sexually harassed by some ugly duckling and she constantly had to be saved! Because obviously, there wasn't room enough in that pretty little head of hers to learn from her first few experiences and stop being alone with men she didn't trust.<br /><br />Now, seriously, if it weren't for Christopher, I swear to god this wouldn't even have gotten a 1 star rating!</span>
  <a data-text-id="896405233930102745" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


